  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 8:51",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ἐάν τις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "if any",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [if a man]) Jesus proves from the future effect, wherewith the Father is about to honour Him, that He and His word have nothing in common with the proud and murderous devil.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τηρήσῃ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "will keep",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), as I keep My Father’s word, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 8:55",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “I know Him, and keep His saying.” We ought ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to keep",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the doctrine of Jesus, by believing in it; His promises, by hoping for them; His injunctions, by obeying them.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "θάνατον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "death",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Jesus hereby shows, that He is not a Samaritan. The Samaritans were Sadducees, opposed to the doctrine of immortality, according to the testimony of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Epiphanius",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". At least the Jews, who speak here, seem to have attributed that error to the Samaritans. Yet I will admit that it was the smaller portion of the latter, who laboured under that error.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "οὐ μὴ θεωρήσῃ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he shall not see",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") A most effectual argument against the maintainers of soul-annihilation.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 51.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Verily, verily.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " This impressive recommencement of discourse implies that a new turn is given to the conversation, and that the gravest solemnity and importance is attached to the utterance. It is impossible that the Jews should have listened unmoved to Christ's rejoinder on their rude taunt, or been unimpressed by the self-composed and lofty way in which the honour of our Lord was calmly entrusted by him to the Father. The Jews may say what they please, call him by any opprobrious name they choose; \"there is One that seeketh\" his glory, and he is content. He has, in earlier portions of this discourse, promised freedom and sonship to those who abide in his word; and now to those who believed on him he says, with extraordinary emphasis, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "If a man",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (any one) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "have kept my word, he shall never behold death.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " This \"keeping\" is more than \"abiding\" in the word. There is the additional notion of intently watching the \"keeping,\" which issues in \"fulfilling\" and \"obeying\" (Meyer and Tholuck); see ver. 55; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 14:15, 21, 23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 15:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 17:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The opposite of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "τηρεῖν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " would be \"to disregard;\" the opposite of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "φυλάσσειν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " would be \"to let slip\" (Westcott). The promise is dazzling: \"He shall never behold,\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " steadily or exhaustively know by experience, what ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "death",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " means and is. He may pass through physical death, he may (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "γεύσηται",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") taste of dissolution, he may come before the judgment seat, he may see corruption (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἰδεῖν διαφθοράν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); but he will not behold (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "θεωρεῖν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") death. He will never know what death is (cf. here; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 4:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 5:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 6:51",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where the Saviour speaks of the \"living water,\" and \"life eternal,\" and \"living bread,\" which whoso partaketh shall never die.. See also ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 11:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). He does not tell his disciples that they shall not see the grave, but that in the deepest sense they shall never die. \"Death\" and \"life\" are words that are lifted into a higher connotation. Death is a moral state, not an event in their physical existence. John 8:51",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Keep (τηρήσῃ)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "See on 1 Peter 1:4.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "See on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Peter 1:4",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Saying (λόγον)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Better, word, as Rev. See on John 8:43.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Better, word, as Rev. See on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "John 8:43",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He shall not see death (θάνατον οὐ μὴ θεωρήσῃ)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The phrase θεωρεῖν θάνατον, to see death, occurs only here in the New Testament. The double negative signifies in nowise, by no means. Θεωρήσῃ see, denoting steady, protracted vision, is purposely used, because the promise contemplates the entire course of the believer's life in Christ. It is not, shall not die forever, but shall live eternally. Upon this life, which is essentially the negation and contradiction of death, the believer enters from the moment of his union with Christ, and moves along its entire course, in time no less than in eternity, seeing only life, and with his back turned on death. The reverse of this truth, in connection with the same verb, is painfully suggestive. The question is pertinent why the Revisers have retained see, and have not substituted behold, as in so many instances. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]